<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1899-03-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1899-03-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="121" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Conger</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1899-03-24"><hi rend="italic">March 24,
                                1899</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Acting consul at Amoy, having asked whether to oppose Japanese
                            concession, was telegraphed March 9 to remonstrate against
                            discrimination or interference with legitimate American interests. This
                            was intended to prevent possible transfer of existing American rights to
                            Japanese administration. He has not been instructed to ask an American
                            concession, but if China is disposed to grant separate concessions at
                            Amoy, we should expect no less consideration than other friendly
                            powers.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hay</hi>.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
